I apologize for any confusion earlier. Yes, you can adjust the layout of the widgets section in the WordPress admin dashboard to make it wider or more comfortable for you to work with. Here's a step-by-step explanation on how to do that:

1. Log in to your WordPress admin dashboard: Start by logging into your WordPress site's admin area by typing your website URL followed by `/wp-admin` in your browser's address bar, then enter your username and password.

2. Navigate to the Widgets screen: Once you're logged in, you'll see the WordPress admin dashboard. On the left-hand side, you'll find a menu called "Appearance." Hover over it, and you'll see a dropdown menu. Click on "Widgets" to access the widgets screen.

3. Adjust the screen layout: In the WordPress admin dashboard, there's a feature called "Screen Options" that allows you to customize the layout of various screens, including the Widgets screen. You'll find the "Screen Options" tab at the top-right corner of the dashboard, next to the "Help" tab.

4. Customize the widgets layout: Click on the "Screen Options" tab. You'll see a dropdown box with various options that you can enable or disable. To make the widgets display wider, you can enable the "Additional CSS Classes" option. This will add an extra class to the widgets screen, allowing you to customize its width using custom CSS.

5. Add custom CSS: To make the widgets display wider, you'll need to add some custom CSS to your theme. You can do this by going to "Appearance" > "Customize" > "Additional CSS" in the WordPress admin menu. Add the following CSS code to make the widgets display wider:

```css
#widgets-right {
    max-width: 100%;
}
#widgets-left {
    max-width: 100%;
}
```

This CSS code will remove the maximum width restrictions on both the left and right columns in the widgets screen, allowing them to expand and take up more space. You can adjust the percentage values to your preference to make the widgets display wider.

6. Save your changes: After adding the custom CSS, click on the "Publish" button to save your changes. Now, when you go back to the Widgets screen, you'll see that the layout has been adjusted, and the widgets display wider for you to work with.

Remember that making changes to the WordPress admin dashboard's layout can affect your overall workflow, so adjust the settings according to your comfort and needs.

